  "opinion": "As a carpenter in Chicago with two young children, I’ve seen firsthand how the world of science often feels like a different universe from my daily life. The gender gap in science isn’t just about numbers—it’s about who gets to see themselves in the stories and tools they use. For instance, when my kids ask why the sky is blue or how bridges stay up, I often have to explain it in simple terms because they’ve never had access to the same kind of scientific exploration as their peers. In my community, the idea that science is ‘for boys’ is still a common belief, even among parents who might not realize how much this shapes their children’s future. I believe we should address this gap not by forcing everyone into the same path, but by creating spaces where everyone feels welcome to ask questions and explore without judgment. For example, local science fairs could be designed to include hands-on activities that appeal to all genders, like building models with wood or testing water quality in lakes. This isn’t about changing science itself—it’s about making sure that the tools and stories of science reflect the diversity of the people who live them. In my own life, I’ve learned that when you give kids the chance to tinker and experiment in a safe space, they start to see science as something they can own, not something reserved for others. The key is to keep it practical, relevant, and rooted in real-world problems that matter to everyone.",
